{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LwWRUV9t8hnF8ciGNK7ALM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: query-layer-discipline\n     3→description: Keep reads in selectors/querysets and keep write logic in services without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Query Layer Discipline (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when introducing new read patterns.\n     9→Implement the file edits directly. Do not return a checklist-only response.\n    10→\n    11→## Required Variables\n    12→\n    13→- `model_name`\n    14→- `queryset_name`\n    15→- `manager_name`\n    16→- `selector_name`\n    17→- `selector_file`\n    18→- `view_name`\n    19→\n    20→## Required Output Contract\n    21→\n    22→1. Modify `models.py`, `selectors.py`, and `views.py`.\n    23→2. In `models.py`, define `class EntityQuerySet(models.QuerySet)` with an `active(self)` method returning `self.filter(status=\"active\")`.\n    24→3. In `models.py`, define `class EntityManager(models.Manager)` with:\n    25→- `get_queryset(self)` returning `EntityQuerySet(self.model, using=self._db)`\n    26→- `active(self)` returning `self.get_queryset().active()`\n    27→4. In `class Entity(models.Model)`, assign `objects = EntityManager()` before the field declarations.\n    28→5. In `selectors.py`, import `Entity` from `.models`.\n    29→6. In `selectors.py`, define `def select_active_entities():` returning a parenthesized chained expression:\n    30→- `Entity.objects.active()`\n    31→- `.select_related()`\n    32→7. In `views.py`, import `select_active_entities` from `.selectors`.\n    33→8. In `entity_list`, assign `records = select_active_entities()` and preserve `return {\"results\": []}`.\n    34→\n    35→## Guardrails\n    36→\n    37→- Avoid query logic scattered in views.\n    38→- Use the exact identifiers provided in the required variables.\n    39→- Do not introduce additional selector helpers or unrelated view changes.\n    40→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"efed26fc-0e8f-4294-8814-1f6415625de2","uuid":"cbc6d411-47cf-4a6d-84ca-4d3aa27b05fe"}
